      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "What is an \"intensional\" context? Basically, it's one in which SI does not hold! This is not very helpful, but the distinction can be drawn by examples: given that Mark Twain wrote Huck Finn and that Sam Clemens was the same person as Mark Twain, then Sam Clemens wrote Huck Finn. The context \"x wrote Huck Finn\" is extensional, which means that we can validly substitute identicals within it. In contrast, if Joe said \"Mark Twain wrote Huck Finn\", it does not follow that he said \"Sam Clemens wrote Huck Finn\", for he may have said no such thing.",
        "spans": [
          {
            "start": 63,
            "end": 65,
            "type": "em"
          },
          {
            "start": 294,
            "end": 295,
            "type": "strong"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "The fallacy of Illicit Substitution of Identicals—or, more colorfully, the Masked Man Fallacy—is an application of SI within an intensional context.",
